1
00:00:02,394 --> 00:00:04,294
♪ ♪

2
00:00:14,639 --> 00:00:15,838
Mrs. Davis?

3
00:00:15,907 --> 00:00:17,040
Uh, yes.

4
00:00:17,108 --> 00:00:18,574
Detective Reagan.

5
00:00:18,643 --> 00:00:21,944
I understand you had an incident
with your ex-husband?

6
00:00:22,013 --> 00:00:23,112
Warren and I are separated.

7
00:00:23,181 --> 00:00:25,648
I served him with divorce papers
this morning.

8
00:00:25,717 --> 00:00:26,849
Okay. So what happened?

9
00:00:26,918 --> 00:00:30,687
Uh, he came over, um,
screaming, crying.

10
00:00:30,755 --> 00:00:32,789
I probably shouldn't
have let him in,

11
00:00:32,857 --> 00:00:34,824
but I thought I could reason
with him.

12
00:00:34,893 --> 00:00:36,459
Did he put his hands on you?

13
00:00:36,528 --> 00:00:38,027
No. No, no, um...

14
00:00:38,096 --> 00:00:39,729
But he said there's no way

15
00:00:39,798 --> 00:00:42,131
he'd ever let me
tear our family apart.

16
00:00:42,200 --> 00:00:43,866
I see.
(gate squeaks open)

17
00:00:45,303 --> 00:00:46,602
(Danny clears throat)
(boy sighs)

18
00:00:46,671 --> 00:00:48,371
You didn't have
to call the police, Mom.

19
00:00:48,440 --> 00:00:51,307
This is our son, Andrew.
Dad was just upset.

20
00:00:51,376 --> 00:00:53,154
Doesn't give him the right
to threaten you guys.

21
00:00:53,178 --> 00:00:55,244
I gotta go.

22
00:01:00,385 --> 00:01:02,418
It's gotta be tough on him.

23
00:01:02,487 --> 00:01:05,321
It is.

24
00:01:05,390 --> 00:01:08,091
I wish it didn't have to be
this way.

25
00:01:08,159 --> 00:01:11,127
Yeah, I understand.
Um, I also understand

26
00:01:11,196 --> 00:01:13,363
that, uh,
Children's Services assigned

27
00:01:13,431 --> 00:01:15,609
an investigative consultant
to your case, is that right?

28
00:01:15,633 --> 00:01:16,899
Uh, yes.

29
00:01:16,968 --> 00:01:19,569
He's been incredibly supportive.

30
00:01:19,637 --> 00:01:20,570
Um...

31
00:01:20,638 --> 00:01:22,305
This is him now.

32
00:01:25,777 --> 00:01:27,210
Morning, Detective.

33
00:01:35,787 --> 00:01:37,920
Hey, that fits
the description

34
00:01:37,989 --> 00:01:39,889
of the vehicle wanted
in connection

35
00:01:39,958 --> 00:01:41,469
with the double homicide
in the Bronx last night.

36
00:01:41,493 --> 00:01:43,426
Good eye.
Run the plate.

37
00:01:43,495 --> 00:01:45,395
JANKO:
Brandon Phelps.

38
00:01:45,463 --> 00:01:47,797
Registration expired
two months ago.

39
00:01:47,866 --> 00:01:49,465
Let's go.

40
00:01:49,534 --> 00:01:51,534
(siren wailing)

41
00:02:10,388 --> 00:02:13,156
Registration's
expired, Brandon.

42
00:02:13,224 --> 00:02:15,391
So write me a ticket
and let me get out of here.

43
00:02:16,761 --> 00:02:18,528
Do me a favor,
lower this rear window.

44
00:02:21,032 --> 00:02:23,199
Now put your hands back
on the wheel, please.

45
00:02:34,913 --> 00:02:38,114
What've we got
here, Brandon?

46
00:02:38,183 --> 00:02:39,982
No idea what that is.
TROY: We're gonna need

47
00:02:40,051 --> 00:02:41,317
to search the vehicle.

48
00:02:41,386 --> 00:02:42,685
Step out of the car.

49
00:02:42,754 --> 00:02:44,620
Now.

50
00:02:44,689 --> 00:02:46,556
Let's go.

51
00:02:47,559 --> 00:02:48,925
Put your hands
on the car.

52
00:03:00,038 --> 00:03:02,605
.38 caliber revolver.

53
00:03:02,674 --> 00:03:04,919
What was the caliber gun used
in those shootings last night?

54
00:03:04,943 --> 00:03:06,943
.38-- Put your hands
behind your back.

55
00:03:07,011 --> 00:03:09,512
What a coincidence.
I didn't shoot nobody.

56
00:03:09,581 --> 00:03:10,813
Guess we'll find out.

57
00:03:10,882 --> 00:03:12,482
Good eye, Janko.

58
00:03:12,550 --> 00:03:15,151
Real good eye.

59
00:03:15,220 --> 00:03:18,054
(handcuffs click)
(sighs) Let's go.

60
00:03:20,892 --> 00:03:22,692
(sighs)

61
00:03:22,760 --> 00:03:25,161
Okay. How did it start?

62
00:03:25,230 --> 00:03:27,597
As a typical noise complaint.

63
00:03:27,665 --> 00:03:30,266
Restaurant manager said
he asked the group in question

64
00:03:30,335 --> 00:03:33,336
to quiet down repeatedly
before calling 911.

65
00:03:33,404 --> 00:03:34,849
And there were calls
from the neighbors

66
00:03:34,873 --> 00:03:36,383
about what had spilled out
onto the sidewalk.

67
00:03:36,407 --> 00:03:37,551
GORMLEY: So a pretty
rowdy group

68
00:03:37,575 --> 00:03:40,176
that was really
getting out of hand.

69
00:03:40,245 --> 00:03:44,046
But also chock-full
of FDNY brass.

70
00:03:44,115 --> 00:03:46,916
Responding officers did not have
that information.

71
00:03:46,985 --> 00:03:51,687
And when did our guys ascertain
that information?

72
00:03:51,756 --> 00:03:54,690
No way to know that,
specifically.

73
00:03:54,759 --> 00:03:59,061
Maybe when they pulled up
and clocked the FDNY badges

74
00:03:59,130 --> 00:04:02,932
and plates on the vehicles
in front of the restaurant?

75
00:04:03,001 --> 00:04:04,767
Could be.

76
00:04:04,836 --> 00:04:06,769
Was exactly.

77
00:04:06,838 --> 00:04:09,105
Point being, our guys
did not arrive on the scene

78
00:04:09,173 --> 00:04:12,141
with any intent other
than to quell the disturbance.

79
00:04:12,210 --> 00:04:14,410
Yet, somehow,

80
00:04:14,479 --> 00:04:18,114
they managed
to arrest Stan Rourke.

81
00:04:18,182 --> 00:04:20,082
Well, yeah.

82
00:04:20,151 --> 00:04:22,785
(laughing): Yeah, well,
that's pretty resourceful,

83
00:04:22,854 --> 00:04:24,153
I'll give us that.

84
00:04:24,222 --> 00:04:26,756
Turning a noise complaint
about a retirement racket

85
00:04:26,824 --> 00:04:30,760
into collaring
the FDNY commissioner.

86
00:04:30,828 --> 00:04:34,430
Boss, all the eyewitnesses said
the exact same thing.

87
00:04:34,499 --> 00:04:36,599
Our guy was appealing
to Commissioner Rourke

88
00:04:36,668 --> 00:04:39,135
who responded by laying hands
on our guy.

89
00:04:39,203 --> 00:04:42,171
Watch out, Sid, there's
an elephant in the room.

90
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:43,806
"Our" guys, "their" guys.

91
00:04:43,875 --> 00:04:46,742
This has been going on
as long as I've been a cop.

92
00:04:46,811 --> 00:04:49,045
Again, boss,
our guys didn't start this.

93
00:04:49,113 --> 00:04:51,280
No, but it just might be

94
00:04:51,349 --> 00:04:53,916
our guys poured gasoline on it.

95
00:04:58,156 --> 00:05:00,957
A.D.A. Erin Reagan.

96
00:05:03,428 --> 00:05:04,927
Thanks so much for coming up.

97
00:05:04,996 --> 00:05:06,206
Pleasure meeting you, Mr. Mayor.

98
00:05:06,230 --> 00:05:07,697
Mayor-elect.

99
00:05:07,765 --> 00:05:09,799
Mr. Mayor-elect.

100
00:05:09,867 --> 00:05:11,267
How about just Peter?

101
00:05:11,336 --> 00:05:12,368
Peter.

102
00:05:12,437 --> 00:05:14,036
Please.

103
00:05:20,278 --> 00:05:22,178
So, congratulations.

104
00:05:22,246 --> 00:05:23,546
Yeah, thanks.

105
00:05:23,615 --> 00:05:26,282
I liked a lot of what you
had to say on the campaign.

106
00:05:26,351 --> 00:05:28,351
Some of which was true...

107
00:05:28,419 --> 00:05:30,286
and some of which
was a combination

108
00:05:30,355 --> 00:05:32,788
of pandering
and wishful thinking.

109
00:05:32,857 --> 00:05:35,057
And which was which?

110
00:05:35,126 --> 00:05:36,993
Doesn't matter, I got the job.

111
00:05:37,061 --> 00:05:39,462
So now all of it has to be true.

112
00:05:39,530 --> 00:05:41,364
Right.

113
00:05:41,432 --> 00:05:44,000
Which is why I've asked you up.

114
00:05:44,068 --> 00:05:46,636
Gulp.

115
00:05:46,704 --> 00:05:49,338
Nah. It's all good.

116
00:05:51,042 --> 00:05:53,142
I don't like your boss's bent.

117
00:05:55,046 --> 00:05:57,013
I didn't know
my boss had a bent.

118
00:05:57,081 --> 00:05:59,582
He thinks accused criminals

119
00:05:59,651 --> 00:06:02,318
and their victims
both have equal rights.

120
00:06:02,387 --> 00:06:04,220
They don't have equal rights.

121
00:06:04,288 --> 00:06:06,522
They are both protected
under the law.

122
00:06:06,591 --> 00:06:08,891
Yes, and rightly so.

123
00:06:08,960 --> 00:06:11,127
But he gets lost in the weeds.

124
00:06:12,530 --> 00:06:15,531
I don't think your office
has the trust that it should.

125
00:06:15,600 --> 00:06:16,699
The people's trust?

126
00:06:16,768 --> 00:06:17,700
That's our customer.

127
00:06:17,769 --> 00:06:18,701
That's who we serve.

128
00:06:18,770 --> 00:06:20,770
Well, we serve the law,
actually.

129
00:06:20,838 --> 00:06:22,371
That, too.

130
00:06:22,440 --> 00:06:24,740
But don't forget the customer.

131
00:06:26,377 --> 00:06:30,446
I'd like to support your run
for Manhattan district attorney.

132
00:06:31,716 --> 00:06:34,083
I... (chuckles)
I don't have a run.

133
00:06:34,152 --> 00:06:35,718
You do now, if you want.

134
00:06:35,787 --> 00:06:37,219
With the mayor's backing.

135
00:06:37,288 --> 00:06:38,387
The mayor-elect.

136
00:06:38,456 --> 00:06:40,623
In a month and a half, mayor.

137
00:06:40,692 --> 00:06:43,325
By a landslide.

138
00:06:43,394 --> 00:06:45,995
You're gonna get a call
from Sam Terhune.

139
00:06:46,064 --> 00:06:48,764
He's been with me since day one.

140
00:06:48,833 --> 00:06:51,901
Have the coffee, hear him out,
share your concerns.

141
00:06:51,969 --> 00:06:55,237
Well, my first concern is that
I am loyal to my office,

142
00:06:55,306 --> 00:06:56,706
and you're asking me to...

143
00:06:56,774 --> 00:06:59,408
Stay loyal to your office.

144
00:06:59,477 --> 00:07:02,445
Mr. Chatwal is not the office.

145
00:07:02,513 --> 00:07:05,514
He's just the guy sitting
in it for now.

146
00:07:12,290 --> 00:07:16,290
